text: #DYK kids ages 5 years & up should get a #COVID19 vaccine? Learn more with a new COVID-19 video now available in American Sign Language (ASL) on CDC’s YouTube channel. Watch the videos here: https://t.co/kYY31uPaFy. https://t.co/wjnaQzlU6u

#CDC will begin to monitor #COVID19 hospitalizations, hospital capacity, and number of cases in each county to inform community-specific recommendations for preventing COVID-19. Learn more in this week’s COVID Data Tracker Weekly Review: https://t.co/F4bAyObDp1. https://t.co/qopj7RLwuF

Recent COVID-NET data show that #COVID19 hospitalization rates for American Indian/Alaska Native people remain high & are the highest of any race/ethnicity group. 

Get vaccinated to protect against severe disease, hospitalization, & death. More: https://t.co/qpYN3dSJL8. https://t.co/hYJeUY5ImO
RT @CDCDirector: NEW: CDC is releasing a new tool to measure and monitor the level of #COVID19 in communities that includes hospitalization…

Parents & Caregivers: When you take your kids to get their #COVID19 vaccine, add them to your v-safe account. Children under 16 years can receive check-ins after getting vaccinated if they have been added to a parent’s or guardian's account. Register now: https://t.co/xSRv5ioLaX. https://t.co/FETLUPuvVk

CDC is updating #COVID19 community recommendations.

CDC’s new COVID-19 Community Level tool classifies every county in the US into low, medium, or high, with recommended prevention measures for each level.

Check your area’s level and learn more here: https://t.co/UZxX67a6M3.

During the emergence of the #Omicron variant in Dec. 2021, adults who were unvaccinated had more than 41 times the risk of #COVID19 death compared w/ adults fully vaccinated & boosted. Get boosted today to protect yourself & loved ones. See the data: https://t.co/t8kVzbKLND. https://t.co/zmMP8JG11U
Learn more about how to protect yourself and others from #COVID19: https://t.co/DmfPOAPMjW.

New @CDCMMWR: #Omicron transmission was high among household contacts. Prevention strategies, like getting #COVID19 vaccines, isolating if you have COVID-19, and masking at home, are important to reduce risk of transmission in household settings. https://t.co/bQD8WpzVW4 https://t.co/Nr7ynU6CuA

Growing evidence continues to show that #COVID19 vaccination during pregnancy is safe and effective. If you are pregnant, talk to your doctor about the benefits of getting vaccinated against COVID-19. Read more: https://t.co/pBVlI6STf8. https://t.co/tj2Y5cjMKc

#COVID19 cases are decreasing across most of the country. The 7-day average of daily new cases is 75,208, a 37.7% decrease from the previous 7-day period. 

Get vaccinated as soon as you can & get a booster when you're eligible.  

More: https://t.co/ZQrL9lFuN9. https://t.co/fTg65TUFru

Parents & Guardians: Getting your child vaccinated against #COVID19 will be similar to getting routine vaccines. 

Find out what you need to know to support your child before, during, and after the appointment: https://t.co/oV6NgGGUSb.

New @CDCMMWR describes how the NFL used #COVID19 testing to allow players and staff to shorten the number of days in isolation during the emergence of the Omicron variant. Learn more: https://t.co/pQjZiJNFb5. https://t.co/w8e7vAVVoY

New in @CDCMMWR: About half of people w/ #COVID19 had a positive antigen test 5–9 days after symptoms or a 1st positive test. During this period, wear masks & avoid close contact w/ people at higher risk for COVID-19, even if ending isolation after 5 days. https://t.co/NpnyOy9ZoE https://t.co/cmnGdFmex1

HCPs: Distinguishing multisystem inflammatory syndrome in children (MIS-C) from severe #COVID19, Kawasaki disease, & toxic shock syndrome can be challenging. Learn about a diagnostic scoring tool to improve timely MIS-C recognition and treatment: https://t.co/YktBo2E7cV. https://t.co/gKh5hJiR43
#HCPs: Attend today’s COCA Call from 2–3 p.m. EST: Updated Guidance for Clinicians on #COVID19 Vaccines. Learn more: https://t.co/0nVJA24sHr. https://t.co/E5Jcf7ohT3
As of February 21, 2022, national forecasts predict 5,400–12,800 new #COVID19 deaths will likely be reported during the week ending March 19. More: https://t.co/rcqjOX3Ypl. https://t.co/zYTCwjKL4o
As of February 21, 2022, national forecasts predict 400–6,600 new #COVID19 hospitalizations will likely be reported on March 18. More: https://t.co/Xys80ZGlxV. https://t.co/lizZ1AQrat

Have questions about getting a #COVID19 booster shot? Learn more with a new COVID-19 video now available in American Sign Language (ASL) on CDC’s YouTube channel. Watch the videos here: https://t.co/0pvjLMKxxC. https://t.co/Vco7I6TCoX

Parents: Vaccinate kids 5 years and older to provide the best protection. 
Mild side effects after your child gets a #COVID19 vaccine are normal & typically last a few days. However, children who get COVID-19 can get very sick & even be hospitalized.
More: https://t.co/oV6NgGGUSb https://t.co/Ab42alKIB5
#HCPs: Attend the next COCA Call, Thursday, February 24, from 2–3 p.m. EST. Topic: Updated Guidance for Clinicians on #COVID19 Vaccines. Learn more: https://t.co/0nVJA24sHr. https://t.co/I0ffShrnTc

School leaders: Regular testing helps keep #COVID19 from spreading. See our toolkit for talking points, FAQs, and graphics to help communicate the importance of regular testing at school. https://t.co/ZSDPe2w4ZQ https://t.co/2PAWuOsaCn

As of Feb. 22, 2022, 253.1 million people have received at least one dose of a #COVID19 vaccine. Of those, 215 million are fully vaccinated. More than 93.2 million people have received a COVID-19 booster dose.

Find a COVID-19 vaccine near you: https://t.co/xbvNiaVJKV. https://t.co/Kds6WHpiui

Parents: Children can get infected with the virus that causes #COVID19 and can get very sick. Dr. Ilan Shapiro explains why the COVID-19 vaccine is your child’s best protection. https://t.co/CPHmdV0Znk

If you are pregnant or are planning for pregnancy, make sure you are up to date with your #COVID19 vaccines, including your booster. Growing evidence shows that COVID-19 vaccination before and during pregnancy is safe and effective. Learn more: https://t.co/pBVlI6STf8. https://t.co/4aGmDUkHyW

HCPs: CDC has updated the list of underlying medical conditions that can increase a patient’s risk of severe #COVID19, incl. people who do little to no physical activity. Other new conditions include primary immunodeficiencies & certain disabilities. More: https://t.co/vebVOidEwS https://t.co/sAW8URMlgd

Open windows can help improve ventilation in your home, but if it’s too cold, cracking a window a little helps. Using better HVAC filters, HEPA purifiers, & kitchen/bathroom exhaust fans can also help reduce #COVID19 particles in the air. See how much: https://t.co/TBVrZob27w. https://t.co/885vNdbgFn

New #COVID19 videos are now available in American Sign Language (ASL) on CDC’s YouTube channel. Learn about a COVID-19 booster shot for people ages 12 years & up and COVID-19 vaccines for kids ages 5 years & up. Watch the videos here: https://t.co/ToKRSVyLHJ. https://t.co/lZU0jvKKxk

Have you gotten all your #COVID19 vaccines? 
People ages 12 years and older are considered up to date on their COVID-19 vaccinations after getting all recommended doses, including a booster.
Find a COVID-19 vaccine near you: https://t.co/2akIUZ14Rd. https://t.co/iJbsfnjLkv

#COVID19 has been difficult for children and adolescents experiencing the loss of parents and caregivers and certain physical and mental health conditions. CDC has resources to help kids cope. Learn more in this week’s COVID Data Tracker Weekly Review: https://t.co/F4bAyObDp1. https://t.co/udMqf2tl9u

Everyone ages 12+ years should get a free COVID-19 booster shot. Get up to date on your COVID-19 vaccination today to help protect you and those you love. Find a COVID-19 vaccine near you: https://t.co/2akIUZ14Rd.

Among people ages 12+, the younger people are less likely to have gotten a #COVID19 booster than older age groups. Only 19.9% of fully vaccinated people ages 12–17 years have received a booster, compared with 68% of fully vaccinated people ages 75+. More: https://t.co/ZIUYQvbbw7. https://t.co/87DIjxYoKn

CDC has updated the list of underlying medical conditions that can make you more likely to get very sick from #COVID19. Learn what’s new and find out if you’re at increased risk: https://t.co/icIT1ibaBG. https://t.co/uUSkqxAyot

You’re up to date on your #COVID19 vaccines when you’ve received all your recommended COVID-19 shots, including a booster when you’re eligible. Check to see what’s recommended for you: https://t.co/009bOerScg. https://t.co/XkeO0PBYbj

New @CDCMMWR finds teen girls had the largest increases in pediatric ED visits for mental health conditions during #COVID19 pandemic compared w/ 2019. Learn more about the mental health of children & teens since the pandemic began. https://t.co/snv1vMT7pG https://t.co/l6ihTEI1ZS

New @CDCMMWR finds overall pediatric ED visits dropped since the pandemic began but visits for #COVID19 increased for children throughout the pandemic. Visits also rose for certain injuries, chronic diseases, & behavioral health concerns. Learn more: https://t.co/QfKEtlzF3G. https://t.co/etxOcmvLD6

You tested positive for #COVID19—should you still get a booster shot? Yes.

Wait until your symptoms get better &  your isolation period has ended to get your booster shot. Talk to your doctor or vaccine provider if you have questions. More about boosters: https://t.co/77CTFuJFcO https://t.co/Uzo4k6Tva4

While #COVID19 cases are dropping across the country, community spread is high. The 7-day average of daily new cases is 121,665, a 43% decrease from the previous 7-day period.
Get vaccinated as soon as you can & get a booster when you're eligible. 
More: https://t.co/25VE6knFJF. https://t.co/lwLRKFLjQq

Is it time for your #COVID19 booster?

Put a reminder in your phone or on your calendar to remember when to get your booster shot. 

When it’s time, find a vaccine near you at https://t.co/2akIUZ14Rd. https://t.co/nco0zYRn9N

@WIRED @CDC_AMD Our @CDC_AMD @WIRED video tweet led to some confusion. To clarify: CDC and our partners conduct genome sequencing analysis of the virus that causes COVID-19. Sequencing of the virus helps identify and monitor the spread and impact of variants. https://t.co/D9iNC7OPFL

HCPs: Due to the #COVID19 pandemic, your patients may need to catch up on their immunizations. Make sure you and your staff are familiar with the 2022 Child and Adolescent Immunization Schedule. Learn more: https://t.co/zClTycU5kW. https://t.co/4WdzWqvwNg

In a new @CDCMMWR, an investigation of a #COVID19 outbreak linked to an indoor convention did not find evidence of widespread transmission during the event, which required and monitored mask use and had high rates of vaccination among attendees. More: https://t.co/BnAXbrWDKY. https://t.co/tCW1kDg4bb

A new @CDCMMWR looking at #COVID19 among a group of vaccinated attendees of an indoor convention that socialized together outside of the conference found there were fewer infections among vaccinated attendees who had received a booster dose. More: https://t.co/dyLrTbk3A5. https://t.co/NPXSBfcFGk

Nursing homes are a primary setting of COVID-19 transmission. #PublicHealthReports research looks at how factors inside these facilities & in communities, such as financial resources, staffing, & local COVID-19 situation, affected spread among residents. https://t.co/ziiqJavpEy https://t.co/Fr3Gg0gEtZ
As of February 14, 2022, national forecasts predict 6,300–13,200 new #COVID19 deaths will likely be reported during the week ending March 12. More: https://t.co/rcqjOX3Ypl. https://t.co/VA8nsS7gmc
As of February 14, 2022, national forecasts predict 900–11,600 new #COVID19 hospitalizations will likely be reported on March 11. More: https://t.co/Xys80ZGlxV. https://t.co/ypQvfm3yt9

If you test positive for COVID-19 & are at risk of becoming very sick, contact a health professional right away to determine if you may be eligible for treatment. Don’t delay, treatment must be started within the first few days to be effective.

More: https://t.co/vqxrQrXHSi. https://t.co/QODADCxrrF

.@CDCGlobal’s latest Updates from the Field highlights CDC’s advances in #GlobalHealthSecurity, our response to #COVID19 & more. Learn how CDC and partners are making a difference worldwide: https://t.co/aipicaIcKI. https://t.co/QNApsmquHm

At this time, people ages 12–17 years only can only get the Pfizer-BioNTech #COVID19 vaccine, so they may only get the Pfizer-BioNTech booster. Learn more about boosters and staying up to date on COVID-19 vaccination: https://t.co/77CTFuJFcO.

If you’re 18 years & older, you can choose which #COVID19 booster you get. mRNA COVID-19 vaccines (Pfizer-BioNTech or Moderna) are preferred although the J&J/Janssen COVID-19 vaccine may be considered in some situations. See which booster is right for you: https://t.co/77CTFuJFcO https://t.co/K0Q4wUYdsU

Remember that #COVID19 nose swab test you took? What happened to the swab? If it was processed with a PCR test, there’s a 10% chance that it ended up in a lab for genomic sequencing analysis. Learn more about the process and its importance: https://t.co/XAHSGANLxu @WIRED @CDC_AMD
School leaders: You want to keep everyone in your school safe and healthy. Regular #COVID19 testing can help. Check out our resources to see how: https://t.co/ZSDPe2w4ZQ. https://t.co/TlSpDJt75o

Anyone can get an infection, and almost any infection, including #COVID19, can lead to sepsis. This #SepsisSurvivor Week, learn specific steps you can take to reduce your risk of sepsis. https://t.co/lhYaTV6osQ https://t.co/1pzXwSg0gP

New @CDCMMWR found #Omicron #COVID19 hospitalization rates among children and adolescents almost 4x as high than during Delta peak. Adolescents who were unvaccinated had 6x as high hospitalization rates compared w/ adolescents who were vaccinated. https://t.co/UiSIELVC7n https://t.co/QeezdwxAlL

Too cold to open windows? Improve ventilation in your home by upgrading your HVAC filter, running a HEPA purifier, and using kitchen/bathroom exhaust fans. See how these actions can help reduce #COVID19 particles in your home’s air: https://t.co/TBVrZob27w. https://t.co/AZf4KF7neM

#Omicron is the dominant variant in the U.S., accounting for nearly all #COVID19 cases. Severe outcomes from Omicron appear lower than during previous periods of high COVID-19 spread, due, in part, to #COVID19 vaccination and boosters. More: https://t.co/F4bAyObDp1. https://t.co/xWz7FxvXOw
